name: The Eyes of Texas
comments: University of Texas fight song. Set to the tune of "I've Been Working on the Railroad" The first public performance of this song was during a varsity minstrel show held at the Hancock Opera House (Austin, Texas) on May 12, 1903. It was sung by a quartet consisting of students (Jim Cannon, Jim Kivlehen, Ralph Porter and Bill Smith) accompanied by the lyricist, John Sinclair, on banjo. It was done as a joke on Univerisity of Texas president William Prather who was known to admonish students with the phrase, 'the eyes of Texas are upon you." This song was first performed at a University of Texas football game when fans started to sing it when U. of Texas faced Texas A&M on Thanksgiving, 1905.
